<DOC><DOCNO> AP880303-0072 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-03-03-88 0651EST</FILEID><FIRST>r a PM-WeatherpageWeather     03-03 0646</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Weatherpage Weather,0664</SECOND><HEAD>Rain, Snow Across Nation's Midsection</HEAD><BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE><TEXT>   A storm system produced showers and thunderstorms across thelower Mississippi Valley as snow fell on other parts of thenation's midsection and tornadoes were reported in Louisiana andTexas.   Behind the storm system, which was centered over southeasternOklahoma, snow advisories were posted Wednesday across parts ofTexas, New Mexico, Oklahoma and Kansas. Up to 7 inches of snow fellin the Texas Panhandle.   Several tornadoes were reported near Duson and Lafayette, La.One person was injured at Duson and 28 aircraft were damaged at theLafayette Regional Airport. A tornado ripped the roofs off mobilehomes and temporarily interrupted power in Galveston, Texas.   Heavy rain and gusty winds accompanied the thunderstorms acrossLouisiana. Almost 2 inches of rain fell Wednesday evening at BatonRouge. Gusts were clocked at 83 mph in Lafayette as thunderstormsrumbled across the area.   Strong wind blew over a house trailer and also caused tree andpower line damage near Baton Rouge. Wind also damaged the roof of ahouse at Opelousas and blew a trailer over at Scott.   Winds were gusty at times behind the storm system; Enid, Okla.,reported gusts to 46 mph Wednesday night.   Rain fell from western Oklahoma across parts of Kansas andMissouri. Almost 2 inches was recorded at McConnell AFB in Wichita,Kan., on Wednesday evening. Rain also extended east across southernIllinois and southern Indiana, and showers were reported fromwestern Tennessee into central Mississippi.   A flood warning was posted for the Deep Fork River in Oklahoma.   Snow advisories were posted across parts of Kansas, Oklahoma andNew Mexico. Up to 3 inches of snow was reported at Liberal andMeade, Kan., and ground blizzard conditions were reported acrossthe region. Rain was changing to freezing rain and sleet acrosssouth-central Kansas early today.   Showers also dampened south-central Arizona, scattered sectionsof the Pacific Northwest, southern New York state and the NewEngland seaboard. Snow was falling over northern lower Michigan andfrom northeast New York state into northern Vermont and NewHampshire.   Showers and thunderstorms were forecast for today from much ofTexas across the lower Mississippi and Tennessee valleys to Georgiaand western South Carolina; rain from southern Missouri across theOhio Valley and mid-Atlantic states to New Jersey; and snow fromsouthern New England across New York and northern Pennsylvania,northern Ohio and central Missouri to parts of New Mexico.   Highs were expected to be in the 20s or 30s from New Englandacross the upper Ohio Valley, the Great Lakes region and the upperhalf of the Mississippi Valley to the Dakotas; the 60s or 70s fromsouthern Virginia and the Carolinas across the Gulf Coast states tothe southern half of Texas, and from the desert Southwest acrossCalifornia to southwest Oregon; a few 80s will appear in extremesouthern Texas and southern Florida. Elsewhere, highs will be inthe 40s or 50s.   Temperatures around the nation at 2 a.m. EST ranged from 5 belowzero at Marquette, Mich., to 71 at Key West, Fla.   Other reports:   _East: Atlanta 57 cloudy; Boston 44 cloudy; Buffalo 30 cloudy;Charleston, S.C. 50 foggy; Cincinnati 41 rain; Cleveland 31 cloudy;Detroit 24 fair; Miami 69 fair; New York 44 cloudy; Philadelphia 45partly cloudy; Pittsburgh 37 foggy; Portland 40 cloudy; Washington48 cloudy.   _Central: Bismarck 18 fair; Chicago 30 cloudy; Dallas-Fort Worth43 windy; Denver 24 fair; Des Moines 26 cloudy; Indianapolis 32rain; Kansas City 32 windy; Minneapolis-St. Paul 20 fair; Nashville54 cloudy; New Orleans 66 rain; St. Louis 36 rain.   _West: Albuquerque 38 snow; Anchorage 28 fair; Las Vegas 58fair; Los Angeles 54 fair; Phoenix 54 cloudy; Salt Lake City 37partly cloudy; San Diego 56 partly cloudy; San Francisco 49 partlycloudy; Seattle 43 partly cloudy.   _Canada: Montreal 14 snow; Toronto 25 fair.</TEXT></DOC>